07/03/23, 13:18 - +91 83407 01368: #include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int n,t,i,j,c,a,b,m;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--)
    {
        cin>>n;
        m=-1;
        for(i=1;i<=n;i++)
        {
            cin>>a>>b>>c;
            if((a==1)||(b==c))
            {
                cout<<"YES"<<"\n";
                m=max(b,c);
            }
        
            else
            {
                if((m>c&&m<=b)||(m>b&&m<=c))
                {
                    cout<<"YES"<<"\n";
                    m=max(b,c);
                }
                else
                {
                    cout<<"NO"<<"\n";
                    m=-1;
                }
            }
        }
    }
	return 0;
}

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* left;
    struct Node* right;
};

struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->left = newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

struct Node* insertNode(struct Node* root, int data) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        root = createNode(data);
        return root;
    }

    if (data < root->data) {
        root->left = insertNode(root->left, data);
    } else if (data > root->data) {
        root->right = insertNode(root->right, data);
    }

    return root;
}

void inorderTraversal(struct Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        return;
    }
    inorderTraversal(root->left);
    printf("%d ", root->data);
    inorderTraversal(root->right);
}

int main() {
    struct Node* root = NULL;
    int n;
    printf("Enter size of array: ");
    scanf("%d",&n);
    int arr[n];
    printf("Enter all elements of array seperated by spaces: ");
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        scanf("%d",&arr[i]);
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        root = insertNode(root, arr[i]);
    }

    printf("Inorder Traversal: ");
    inorderTraversal(root);
    printf("\n");

   return 0;
}
19/06/23, 11:02 - +91 98175 44050: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Structure for a linked list node
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

// Function to insert a new node at the end of the linked list
void insertNode(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;

    if (*head == NULL) {
        *head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    struct Node* current = *head;
    while (current->next != NULL)
        current = current->next;

    current->next = newNode;
}

// Function to calculate the average of the linked list elements
float calculateAverage(struct Node* head) {
    int sum = 0;
    int count = 0;
    struct Node* current = head;

    while (current != NULL) {
        sum += current->data;
        count++;
        current = current->next;
    }

    if (count == 0)
        return 0;

    return (float)sum / count;
}

int main() {
    int size, i, data;
    struct Node* head = NULL;

    printf("Enter the size of the linked list: ");
    scanf("%d", &size);

    printf("Enter the elements of the linked list:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &data);
        insertNode(&head, data);
    }

    float average = calculateAverage(head);
    printf("The average of the linked list elements is: %.2f\n", average);

    // Free memory
    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current != NULL) {
        struct Node* temp = current;
        current = current->next;
        free(temp);
    }

    return 0;
}

#include <stdlib.h>

// Structure for a linked list node
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

// Function to insert a new node at the end of the linked list
void insertNode(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;

    if (*head == NULL) {
        *head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    struct Node* current = *head;
    while (current->next != NULL)
        current = current->next;

    current->next = newNode;
}

// Function to find the maximum value in the linked list
int findMax(struct Node* head) {
    int max = head->data;
    struct Node* current = head->next;

    while (current != NULL) {
        if (current->data > max)
            max = current->data;

        current = current->next;
    }

    return max;
}

int main() {
    int size, i, data;
    struct Node* head = NULL;

    printf("Enter the size of the linked list: ");
    scanf("%d", &size);

    printf("Enter the elements of the linked list:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &data);
        insertNode(&head, data);
    }

    int max = findMax(head);
    printf("The maximum value in the linked list is: %d\n", max);

    // Free memory
    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current != NULL) {
        struct Node* temp = current;
        current = current->next;
        free(temp);
    }

    return 0;
}

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};


void insertAtBeginning(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = *head;
    *head = newNode;
}


void display(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current != NULL) {
        printf("%d -> ", current->data);
        current = current->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");
}


void swap(struct Node* a, struct Node* b) {
    int temp = a->data;
    a->data = b->data;
    b->data = temp;
}

void selectionSort(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* current = head;
    struct Node* minNode;

    
    while (current != NULL) {
        minNode = current;

        
        struct Node* temp = current->next;
        while (temp != NULL) {
            if (temp->data < minNode->data)
                minNode = temp;
            temp = temp->next;
        }

        
        swap(current, minNode);
        current = current->next;
    }
}

int main() {
    
    struct Node* head = NULL;
    insertAtBeginning(&head, 5);
    insertAtBeginning(&head, 3);
    insertAtBeginning(&head, 8);
    insertAtBeginning(&head, 2);
    insertAtBeginning(&head, 1);

    printf("Original Linked List: ");
    display(head);

    
    selectionSort(head);

    printf("Sorted Linked List: ");
    display(head);

¬†¬†¬†¬†return¬†0;
}

#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* left;
    struct Node* right;
};

struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->left = NULL;
    newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

bool isCompleteBinaryTree(struct Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return true;

    bool flag = false;
    struct Node** queue = (struct Node**)malloc(sizeof(struct Node*) * 1000);
    int front = 0, rear = 0;
    queue[rear++] = root;

    while (front < rear) {
        struct Node* temp = queue[front++];

        if (temp->left == NULL)
            flag = true;
        else if (flag)
            return false;
        else
            queue[rear++] = temp->left;

        if (temp->right == NULL)
            flag = true;
        else if (flag)
            return false;
        else
            queue[rear++] = temp->right;
    }

    return true;
}

void freeTree(struct Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return;

    freeTree(root->left);
    freeTree(root->right);
    free(root);
}

int main() {
    int rootData, leftData, rightData;

    printf("Enter the value for the root node: ");
    scanf("%d", &rootData);
    struct Node* root = createNode(rootData);

    printf("Enter the value for the left child of the root: ");
    scanf("%d", &leftData);
    root->left = createNode(leftData);

    printf("Enter the value for the right child of the root: ");
    scanf("%d", &rightData);
    root->right = createNode(rightData);

    if (isCompleteBinaryTree(root))
        printf("The binary tree is a complete binary tree.\n");
    else
        printf("The binary tree is not a complete binary tree.\n");

    freeTree(root);

    return 0;
}

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

void swap(struct Node* a, struct Node* b) {
    int temp = a->data;
    a->data = b->data;
    b->data = temp;
}

void selectionSort(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* current = head;

    while (current != NULL) {
        struct Node* smallest = current;
        struct Node* ptr = current->next;

        while (ptr != NULL) {
            if (ptr->data < smallest->data) {
                smallest = ptr;
            }
            ptr = ptr->next;
        }

        swap(current, smallest);
        current = current->next;
    }
}

void printList(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* ptr = head;
    while (ptr != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", ptr->data);
        ptr = ptr->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

void insert(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = *head;
    *head = newNode;
}

int main() {
    struct Node* head = NULL;

    insert(&head, 5);
    insert(&head, 2);
    insert(&head, 9);
    insert(&head, 1);
    insert(&head, 7);

    printf("Linked list before sorting:\n");
    printList(head);

    selectionSort(head);

    printf("Linked list after sorting:\n");
    printList(head);

    return 0;
}

#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* firstChild;  
    struct Node* nextSibling; 
};


struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->firstChild = newNode->nextSibling = NULL;
    return newNode;
}


bool isCompleteTree(struct Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return true;

    bool flag = false;
    struct Node* queue[100]; 
    int front = -1, rear = -1;
    queue[++rear] = root;

    while (rear != front) {
        struct Node* temp = queue[++front];

        if (temp->firstChild) {
            if (flag == true)
                return false;

            queue[++rear] = temp->firstChild;
        } else {
            flag = true;
        }

        struct Node* sibling = temp->firstChild;
        while (sibling) {
            if (flag == true)
                return false;

            queue[++rear] = sibling;
            sibling = sibling->nextSibling;
        }
    }

    return true;
}

int main() {
    
    struct Node* root = createNode(1);
    root->firstChild = createNode(2);
    root->firstChild->nextSibling = createNode(3);
    root->firstChild->nextSibling->nextSibling = createNode(4);
    root->firstChild->firstChild = createNode(5);
    root->firstChild->firstChild->nextSibling = createNode(6);

    
    if (isCompleteTree(root))
        printf("The tree follows the complete tree property.\n");
    else
        printf("The tree does not follow the complete tree property.\n");

¬†¬†¬†¬†return¬†0;
}

19/06/23, 12:05 - Arth Iiit: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Structure for a node in the linked list
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

// Function to create a new node
struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed.\n");
        exit(1);
    }
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

// Function to insert a node at the end of the linked list
struct Node* insertNode(struct Node* head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(data);

    if (head == NULL)
        return newNode;

    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current->next != NULL)
        current = current->next;

    current->next = newNode;
    return head;
}

// Function to perform bubble sort on the linked list
void bubbleSort(struct Node* head) {
    if (head == NULL || head->next == NULL)
        return;

    int swapped;
    struct Node* current;
    struct Node* last = NULL;

    do {
        swapped = 0;
        current = head;

        while (current->next != last) {
            if (current->data > current->next->data) {
                // Swap the data of current and next nodes
                int temp = current->data;
                current->data = current->next->data;
                current->next->data = temp;
                swapped = 1;
            }
            current = current->next;
        }
        last = current;
    } while (swapped);
}

// Function to print the linked list
void printList(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", current->data);
        current = current->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

// Function to free the memory allocated for the linked list
void freeList(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* current = head;
    while (current != NULL) {
        struct Node* temp = current;
        current = current->next;
        free(temp);
    }
}

int main() {
    struct Node* head = NULL;
    int numNodes;

    printf("Enter the number of nodes in the linked list: ");
    scanf("%d", &numNodes);

    printf("Enter the elements of the linked list:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < numNodes; i++) {
        int data;
        printf("Node %d: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d", &data);
        head = insertNode(head, data);
    }

    printf("Linked list before sorting: ");
    printList(head);

    bubbleSort(head);

    printf("Linked list after sorting: ");
    printList(head);

    // Free the memory allocated for the linked list
    freeList(head);

    return 0;
}

19/06/23, 12:06 - Arth Iiit: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Structure for a binary tree node
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* left;
    struct Node* right;
};

// Function to create a new node
struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed.\n");
        exit(1);
    }
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->left = NULL;
    newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

// Function to insert a node in the binary tree
struct Node* insertNode(struct Node* root, int data) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return createNode(data);

    if (data < root->data)
        root->left = insertNode(root->left, data);
    else if (data > root->data)
        root->right = insertNode(root->right, data);

    return root;
}

// Function to check if the binary tree is a strict binary tree
int isStrictBinaryTree(struct Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return 1;

    // If a node has only one child or no child, it's not a strict binary tree
    if ((root->left == NULL && root->right != NULL) || (root->left != NULL && root->right == NULL))
        return 0;

    // Recursively check the left and right subtrees
    return (isStrictBinaryTree(root->left) && isStrictBinaryTree(root->right));
}

int main() {
    struct Node* root = NULL;
    int numNodes;

    printf("Enter the number of nodes in the binary tree: ");
    scanf("%d", &numNodes);

    printf("Enter the binary tree values:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < numNodes; i++) {
        int data;
        printf("Node %d: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d", &data);
        root = insertNode(root, data);
    }

    if (isStrictBinaryTree(root))
        printf("The binary tree is a strict binary tree.\n");
    else
        printf("The binary tree is not a strict binary tree.\n");

    return 0;
}

struct Node *newNode(char k)

bool isFullTree (struct Node* root)
{
	if (root == NULL)
		return true;
	if (root->left == NULL && root->right == NULL)
		return true;
	if ((root->left) && (root->right))
		return (isFullTree(root->left) && isFullTree(root->right));

	return false;
}

19/06/23, 12:15 - +91 82258 47505: #include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

typedef struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* left;
    struct Node* right;
} Node;

Node* createNode(int data) {
    Node* newNode = (Node*)malloc(sizeof(Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed!\n");
        exit(1);
    }
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->left = NULL;
    newNode->right = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

Node* insertNode(Node* root, int data) {
    if (root == NULL) {
        // The tree is empty, create a new root node
        return createNode(data);
    } else {
        // The tree is not empty, insert the new node recursively
        if (data <= root->data)
            root->left = insertNode(root->left, data);
        else
            root->right = insertNode(root->right, data);
        return root;
    }
}

int isStrictBinaryTree(Node* root) {
    // Base case: an empty tree is strict
    if (root == NULL)
        return 1;

    // If the node has no children, it is a leaf node
    if (root->left == NULL && root->right == NULL)
        return 1;

    // If the node has only one child, it is not strict
    if (root->left == NULL || root->right == NULL)
        return 0;

    // Recursively check the left and right subtrees
    return isStrictBinaryTree(root->left) && isStrictBinaryTree(root->right);
}

void freeTree(Node* root) {
    if (root == NULL)
        return;
    freeTree(root->left);
    freeTree(root->right);
    free(root);
}

int main() {
    Node* root = NULL;
    int numNodes, data;

    printf("Enter the number of nodes in the binary tree: ");
    scanf("%d", &numNodes);

    printf("Enter the values of the nodes:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < numNodes; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &data);
        root = insertNode(root, data);
    }

    int isStrict = isStrictBinaryTree(root);

    if (isStrict)
        printf("The binary tree is strict.\n");
    else
        printf("The binary tree is not strict.\n");

    freeTree(root);

    return 0;
}

23/08/23, 12:49 - Gaurav Iiit It: To solve the recurrence equation T(t) = 2T(t - 1) + t, you can use the substitution method. Let's go step by step:

1. Start with the recurrence equation:
   T(t) = 2T(t - 1) + t

2. Make a substitution to simplify the equation:
   Let S(t) = T(t) - (t + 1)

3. Now, substitute S(t) back into the original equation:
   S(t) + (t + 1) = 2[S(t - 1) + t] + t

4. Expand and simplify:
   S(t) + t + 1 = 2S(t - 1) + 2t + t

5. Rearrange terms:
   S(t) = 2S(t - 1)

6. Now, we have a simpler recurrence relation:
   S(t) = 2S(t - 1)

This recurrence relation is much simpler and can be solved easily. 

7. We can see that S(t) is a geometric sequence with the initial condition S(1) = T(1) - (1 + 1) = 1 - 2 = -1.

8. So, S(t) = (-1) * 2^(t-1)

9. Now, we need to find T(t) which is T(t) = S(t) + t + 1.

10. Plug in the value of S(t):
    T(t) = (-1) * 2^(t-1) + t + 1

So, the solution to the recurrence equation T(t) = 2T(t - 1) + t is:

T(t) = (-1) * 2^(t-1) + t + 1

Hope you're doing well!

Recently, I got to know about a scammer who is asking for money to join clubs, societies, sports, etc.
So I just want to inform you all to beware of these kinds of scams and frauds.
Remember you don't have to pay anything to college except your college fees, hostel and mess fees.
Also, don't get fooled by any kind of WhatsApp forwarded message and that person who is trying to sell their workshop, course, or anything!
You don't have to buy any kind of stuff which is paid even not famous paid courses as of now. 
There are plenty of free resources available on the internet for free. 
So please don't misuse your parent's hard-earned money.

We'll share the resources with you soon!

28/08/23, 17:15 - +91 97525 75930: We're thrilled to announce the upcoming Smart India Hackathon 2023, an incredible opportunity for college students to showcase their problem-solving skills and technical ingenuity on a national stage. The event is a platform that encourages collaboration and innovation to address real-world challenges faced by industries and organizations.
Smart India Hackathon (SIH) is an initiative by the Government of India that invites students to form teams and propose inventive solutions to the problem statements presented by various ministries and organizations. By participating, you get a chance to not only apply your classroom knowledge to practical situations but also to connect with industry professionals, experts, and fellow students from diverse backgrounds.

https://www.sih.gov.in/sih2023PS Problems Set

Why should you consider being part of SIH 2023? Not only will you enhance your problem-solving and teamwork skills, but you'll also have the chance to win attractive prizes, secure internships, and even explore potential job opportunities. Beyond the personal gains, your participation contributes to the larger goal of advancing technology and innovation in our country.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dGBt8_QUguY&ab_channel=HackathonsofInnovationCell%2CMoE

To participate, form a team of up to 6 members including one female member compulsorily and register on the official Smart India Hackathon. Keep an eye out for the release of problem statements from different ministries, and work together with your team to develop innovative solutions that could shape the future.
For further details, please visit the official Smart India Hackathon 2023 website https://www.sih.gov.in/sih 2023 .

If you are interested form your team and inform us ASAP

For any queries, feel free contact us

IEEE IIIT Bhopal Student Branch (filed), Team

08/09/23, 17:36 - Puru Arora CSE: Dear IIIT Bhopal Students,

Exciting news! The Student Council of IIIT Bhopal is thrilled to announce that we are planning to organize the very first-ever Cultural Fest of our beloved institution. This grand event promises to be a celebration of art, culture, creativity, and diversity that will bring our entire IIIT Bhopal family together for an unforgettable experience.

But, before we can set the stage for this amazing journey, we need your help! We believe that the name of our Cultural Fest should reflect the spirit and essence of IIIT Bhopal, and who better to come up with the perfect name than our very own students.

We are inviting all students to participate in the "Name the Fest" contest and suggest a name that captures the unique vibrancy and ethos of our institution. Your creativity and innovation can leave a lasting mark on IIIT Bhopal's history.

Here's how you can participate:

1. Submit your festival name suggestion through this Google Form: [Insert Google Form Link].

2. Be sure to explain why you think your suggested name represents our IIIT Bhopal community so well. A few lines about your choice will go a long way in helping us understand your vision.

3. The Student Council will review all submissions and select the most fitting and creative name for our Cultural Fest.

What's in it for you?

- The student who suggests the chosen name will receive special recognition and a prominent role in the fest's inauguration.

- Plus, you'll have the satisfaction of knowing that your idea played a significant role in shaping this historic event.

Let's come together and make this first-ever Cultural Fest a memorable one. We can't wait to see your suggestions and look forward to your creative contributions.

Stay tuned for more updates on the Cultural Fest. Thank you for being a part of this exciting journey!
Contest Link - https://forms.gle/UL3YZK6rKowv4uBZA
Deadline is Today 11 PM

Warm regards,
Student Council
IIIT Bhopal

09/11/23, 12:13 - Gaurav Iiit It: // C++ program to solve fractional Knapsack Problem
 
#include <bits/stdc++.h>

using namespace std;
 
// Structure for an item which stores weight and
// corresponding value of Item

struct Item {

    int profit, weight;
 

    // Constructor

    Item(int profit, int weight)

    {

        this->profit = profit;

        this->weight = weight;

    }
};
 
// Comparison function to sort Item 
// according to profit/weight ratio

static bool cmp(struct Item a, struct Item b)
{

    double r1 = (double)a.profit / (double)a.weight;

    double r2 = (double)b.profit / (double)b.weight;

    return r1 > r2;
}
 
// Main greedy function to solve problem

double fractionalKnapsack(int W, struct Item arr[], int N)
{

    // Sorting Item on basis of ratio

    sort(arr, arr + N, cmp);
 

    double finalvalue = 0.0;
 

    // Looping through all items

    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {

         

        // If adding Item won't overflow, 

        // add it completely

        if (arr[i].weight <= W) {

            W -= arr[i].weight;

            finalvalue += arr[i].profit;

        }
 

        // If we can't add current Item, 

        // add fractional part of it

        else {

            finalvalue

                += arr[i].profit

                   * ((double)W / (double)arr[i].weight);

            break;

        }

    }
 

    // Returning final value

    return finalvalue;
}
 
// Driver code

int main()
{

    int W = 50;

    Item arr[] = { { 60, 10 }, { 100, 20 }, { 120, 30 } };

    int N = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);
 

    // Function call

    cout << fractionalKnapsack(W, arr, N);

    return 0;
}

01/12/23, 15:45 - +91 99096 93021: Here is the solution for question 5:

The binary string is:
0011000101111101100111011101100000100111010010101

The letter frequencies are:
letter a h v w e t l o  
frequency 1 1 1 1 2 2 2 3

Constructing Huffman tree:

                  Root
                 /     \
             e,t       o  
            /  \      /  \
          l    a    w    h
         /                \ 
       v                  v

Assigning codes:
a: 0
e: 10
t: 11 
l: 110
o: 00
w: 010
h: 011
v: 111

Decoding the binary string: 

0011000101111101100111011101100000100111010010101

Splitting based on codes:
00 11 00 01 0111 1101 100 1110 11101 100001 0011101 0010101

Mapping to letters:
o   t    a   e    l      o     w     h      v       e       o

Therefore, the decoded song title is: "to all who"

The key steps are:
1. Build Huffman tree based on frequencies 
2. Assign codes to letters based on tree branches
3. Split binary string based on assigned codes
4. Map split binary fragments to letters

Let me know if you need any clarification or have additional questions!

05/03/24, 10:07 - +91 70676 66755: **Software Requirements Specification (SRS) for Hotel Management System**

**1. Introduction**

1.1 Purpose

The purpose of this document is to outline the software requirements for the development of a comprehensive Hotel Management System (HMS) that efficiently handles various aspects of hotel operations.

1.2 Scope

The Hotel Management System will cover functionalities such as reservation management, room allocation, guest check-in/check-out, billing, inventory management, and reporting.

1.3 Definitions, Acronyms, and Abbreviations

- HMS: Hotel Management System
- GUI: Graphical User Interface
- API: Application Programming Interface

**2. System Overview**

2.1 System Description

The Hotel Management System is designed to streamline hotel operations, enhance guest experiences, and provide efficient management tools for staff.

2.2 System Features

- Reservation Management
- Room Allocation and Availability
- Guest Check-in/Check-out
- Billing and Invoicing
- Inventory Management (e.g., food, beverages, supplies)
- Reporting and Analytics

**3. Functional Requirements**

3.1 Reservation Management

- The system shall allow users to create, modify, and cancel reservations.
- Users should be able to view room availability and select suitable options.
- Confirmation emails should be sent to guests upon successful reservation.

3.2 Room Allocation and Availability

- The system shall automatically update room availability based on reservations.
- Users should be able to allocate specific rooms manually if needed.

3.3 Guest Check-in/Check-out

- The system shall support a quick and efficient check-in/check-out process.
- Guest details and preferences should be easily accessible for staff.

3.4 Billing and Invoicing

- The system shall generate accurate bills based on room rates and additional services.
- Invoices should be printable and available in electronic format.

3.5 Inventory Management

- The system shall track and manage inventory for various hotel resources.
- Low stock alerts should be generated for timely restocking.

**4. Non-Functional Requirements**

4.1 Performance

- The system should support a minimum of 500 simultaneous users.
- Response time for common operations should be less than 2 seconds.

4.2 Reliability

- The system should have a 99.9% uptime.
- Regular data backups should be performed to prevent data loss.

4.3 Security

- User authentication and authorization mechanisms should be implemented.
- Sensitive guest information must be encrypted.

**5. User Interface Design**

5.1 GUI Design

- The system shall have an intuitive and user-friendly interface.
- Consistent design elements should be applied across all modules.

**6. System Interfaces**

6.1 External Interfaces

- The HMS shall integrate with payment gateways for seamless transactions.
- API integration with third-party booking platforms may be required.

**7. Reporting Requirements**

7.1 Standard Reports

- The system shall generate daily, weekly, and monthly reports on reservations, occupancy, and revenue.

**8. Constraints**

- The system must be compatible with major web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari).

**9. Conclusion**

This Software Requirements Specification outlines the key functionalities and requirements for the development of a Hotel Management System. It serves as a foundation for system design, development, and testing phases.

01/05/24, 10:51 - Nishant Bigshow: **Software Requirements Specification (SRS) for Website Design**

**1. Introduction:**
   Define requirements for a business website.

**2. Scope:**
   Multiple pages: homepage, services, about us, contact.

**3. Functional Requirements:**
   - Homepage: Intro, navigation.
   - Services: List with details.
   - About Us: Company info, team.
   - Contact: Info, form.
   - Responsive design for all devices.

**4. Non-Functional Requirements:**
   - Fast loading, SSL security.
   - User-friendly, compatible with major browsers.

**5. Assumptions and Constraints:**
   - Client provides content.
   - Developed in HTML/CSS/JS.
   - Budget and time constraints apply.

**End of Document**
01/05/24, 10:54 - Nishant Bigshow: **Software Requirements Specification (SRS) for Website Design**

**1. Introduction:**
   The purpose of this document is to define the requirements for the development of a website. The website aims to provide information about a business, its services, and contact details to its users.

**2. Scope:**
   The website will consist of multiple pages including a homepage, services page, about us page, contact page, and potentially others as needed. It will be accessible to users on desktop and mobile devices.

**3. Functional Requirements:**
   3.1 **Homepage:**
      - Display a visually appealing layout introducing the business.
      - Include navigation links to other pages.
      - Highlight key services or products.
   3.2 **Services Page:**
      - List all services provided by the business.
      - Provide detailed information about each service.
   3.3 **About Us Page:**
      - Present information about the company, its history, mission, and values.
      - Include team member profiles if applicable.
   3.4 **Contact Page:**
      - Display contact information including address, phone number, and email.
      - Include a contact form for users to submit inquiries.
   3.5 **Responsive Design:**
      - Ensure the website is optimized for various screen sizes.
      - Implement responsive design techniques to maintain usability on all devices.

**4. Non-Functional Requirements:**
   4.1 **Performance:**
      - Ensure fast loading times for all pages.
   4.2 **Security:**
      - Implement SSL to ensure secure data transmission.
      - Employ CAPTCHA or similar techniques to prevent spam.
   4.3 **Usability:**
      - Keep the layout simple and intuitive for easy navigation.
      - Ensure readability of text and accessibility features.
   4.4 **Compatibility:**
      - Ensure compatibility across major web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge).
      - Compatibility with older browser versions may be considered but not prioritized.

**5. Assumptions and Constraints:**
   - Content will be provided by the client.
   - The website will be developed using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.
   - Budget and time constraints will be adhered to during development.

**6. Glossary:**
   - SSL: Secure Sockets Layer
   - CAPTCHA: Completely Automated Public Turing test to tell Computers and Humans Apart

**7. Revision History:**
   - Version 1.0: Initial draft

**End of Document**
01/05/24, 10:59 - Rishit Iiit IT: Sure, here's a simplified Software Requirements Specification (SRS) outline for designing a website:

1. **Introduction:**
   - Purpose
   - Scope
   - Definitions, acronyms, and abbreviations
   - References
   - Overview of the document

2. **Overall Description:**
   - Product perspective
   - Product functions
   - User characteristics
   - Constraints
   - Assumptions and dependencies

3. **Specific Requirements:**
   - External interface requirements
     - User interfaces
     - Hardware interfaces
     - Software interfaces
     - Communication interfaces
   - Functional requirements
   - Performance requirements
   - Design constraints
   - Software system attributes
     - Reliability
     - Availability
     - Security
     - Maintainability
     - Portability

4. **Appendices:**
   - Glossary
   - Index
   - References

This outline provides a structured approach to document the requirements for designing a website. Each section should be tailored to fit the specific needs and goals of the project.

29/08/24, 12:21 - Gaurav Iiit It: Significance of Network Devices
Network devices are the backbone of modern communication and data transfer. They enable the interconnection of computers, servers, and other electronic devices, allowing for efficient sharing of information and resources. Here are some key significances of network devices:

1. Interconnectivity:
Global Reach: Network devices facilitate the interconnection of computers and networks worldwide, enabling global communication and collaboration.
Local Networks: They create local networks within organizations, homes, and educational institutions, allowing for shared resources and efficient communication.
2. Data Transmission:
Efficient Transfer: Network devices transmit data packets between devices, ensuring efficient and reliable data transfer.
High Speed: Modern network devices support high-speed data transmission, enabling faster downloads, uploads, and streaming.
3. Resource Sharing:
Shared Resources: Network devices allow for the sharing of resources like printers, scanners, and storage devices among multiple users.
Cost-Effective: This shared access reduces the need for individual devices, leading to cost savings.
4. Access to Information:
Internet Access: Network devices provide access to the internet, a vast repository of information and resources.
Intranet Access: They enable access to internal company networks (intranets), facilitating information sharing and collaboration within organizations.
5. Remote Access:
Work from Anywhere: Network devices allow for remote access to computers and networks, enabling remote work and flexible work arrangements.
Virtual Private Networks (VPNs): They can be used to create secure connections over public networks, ensuring privacy and data security.
6. Business Continuity:
Disaster Recovery: Network devices play a crucial role in disaster recovery plans, allowing for data backup and restoration in case of system failures or disasters.
Redundancy: Network redundancy can be implemented using devices like routers and switches to ensure uninterrupted network connectivity.
Common Network Devices:

Routers: Direct traffic between networks.
Switches: Connect devices within a network.
Modems: Connect to the internet.
Hubs: Simple devices that broadcast data to all connected devices.
Firewalls: Protect networks from unauthorized access.
In conclusion, network devices are essential for modern communication, collaboration, and access to information. They enable the interconnection of devices, facilitate data transfer, and provide a foundation for various applications and services.

06/09/24, 12:50 - Gaurav Iiit It: Block diagram bhjta hu abhi
06/09/24, 12:54 - +91 95849 44475: Here are the digital image acquisition steps with block diagram elements:

*Step 1: Image Capture*

- *Sensor*: Converts light into electrical signals (e.g., CCD or CMOS)
- *Lens*: Focuses light onto the sensor
- *Aperture*: Controls light intensity
- *Shutter*: Controls exposure time

*Step 2: Analog-to-Digital Conversion (ADC)*

- *Analog Signal*: Electrical signal from sensor
- *ADC*: Converts analog signal to digital data

*Step 3: Image Processing*

- *Digital Signal Processor (DSP)*: Performs image processing tasks (e.g., filtering, enhancement)
- *Memory*: Stores processed image data

*Step 4: Image Storage*

- *Storage Media*: Stores image data (e.g., hard drive, memory card)
- *File Format*: Formats image data for storage (e.g., JPEG, TIFF)

*Step 5: Image Display*

- *Display Device*: Shows the acquired image (e.g., monitor, printer)
- *Display Controller*: Controls image display

Block Diagram:
```
                                      +---------------+
                                      |  Image Capture  |
                                      +---------------+
                                             |
                                             |
                                             v
                                      +---------------+
                                      |  Analog-to-    |
                                      |  Digital Conversion|
                                      +---------------+
                                             |
                                             |
                                             v
                                      +---------------+
                                      |  Image Processing|
                                      |  (DSP)          |
                                      +---------------+
                                             |
                                             |
                                             v
                                      +---------------+
                                      |  Image Storage  |
                                      |  (Storage Media) |
                                      +---------------+
                                             |
                                             |
                                             v
                                      +---------------+
                                      |  Image Display  |
                                      |  (Display Device)|
                                      +---------------+
```
Note: This is a simplified block diagram, and actual image acquisition systems may include additional components or variations on these steps.

17/09/24, 12:22 - Gaurav Iiit It: N-layered architecture divides networks into layers for easier management. OSI model defines 7 layers:

Physical: Transmits bits.
Data Link: Ensures reliable data transfer.
Network: Routes packets.
Transport: Provides reliable end-to-end communication.
Session: Manages communication sessions.
Presentation: Translates data.
Application: Provides services to users.
17/09/24, 12:23 - Gaurav Iiit It: <Media omitted>
17/09/24, 12:26 - Gaurav Iiit It: Taxonomy of Guided and Unguided Media

Guided Media

Guided media transmit signals along a physical path. This path can be a wire, cable, or optical fiber.

Twisted Pair:
Unshielded Twisted Pair (UTP): Most common type, used in Ethernet networks, susceptible to interference.
Shielded Twisted Pair (STP): Provides better shielding against interference, used in high-noise environments or for critical applications.
Coaxial Cable:
Used for cable television and broadband internet, has a central conductor surrounded by an insulator and a shield.
Optical Fiber:
Uses light to transmit data, offers high bandwidth, low attenuation, and immunity to electromagnetic interference.
Unguided Media

Unguided media transmit signals through the air or space without a physical guide.

Radio Waves:
Used for various applications, including radio broadcasting, cellular phones, and wireless networks.
Microwaves:
Higher frequency radio waves used for satellite communication, radar, and microwave ovens.
Infrared (IR):
Used for short-range communication, such as remote controls and wireless networks.
Why Bandwidth is Important for Fibre Optic Cables

Bandwidth, the rate at which data can be transmitted, is a crucial factor in the widespread adoption of fiber optic cables in data communication and networking.

High Data Capacity: Fiber optic cables can handle significantly higher data rates than other guided media, making them ideal for applications that require large amounts of data transmission, such as video streaming, online gaming, and cloud computing.
Long Distances: Fiber optic cables can transmit data over long distances without significant signal degradation, making them suitable for connecting networks across cities, countries, and even continents.
Low Attenuation: Fiber optic cables have very low attenuation, meaning that signals can travel long distances without losing much of their strength. This enables efficient data transmission over extended networks.
Immunity to Interference: Fiber optic cables are not susceptible to electromagnetic interference (EMI), which can degrade the quality of signals transmitted over other types of cables. This makes them more reliable and less prone to errors.
Scalability: Fiber optic cables can be easily upgraded to support higher data rates as technology advances, making them a future-proof choice for network infrastructure.
